SIMPLE: lucifer
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lucifer
<hw>Lu"ci*fer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., bringing light,
<pos>n.</pos>, the morning star, fr. <ets>lux</ets>, <ets>lucis</ets>,
light + <ets>ferre</ets> to bring.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The planet Venus, when appearing as the morning
star; -- applied in Isaiah by a metaphor to a king of Babylon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How art thou fallen from heaven, O <qex>Lucifer</qex>, son of the
morning! how art thou cut down to the ground which didst weaken the
nations!</q> <rj><qau>Is. xiv. 12.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Tertullian and Gregory the Great understood this passage of Isaiah
in reference to the fall of Satan; in consequence of which the name
<qex>Lucifer</qex> has since been applied to Satan.</q>
<rj><qau>Kitto.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, Satan.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How wretched⟦br⟧
Is that poor man that hangs on princes' favors! . . . ⟦br⟧
When he falls, he falls like <qex>Lucifer</qex>,⟦br⟧
Never to hope again.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A match{1} made of a sliver of wood tipped with a
combustible substance, and ignited by friction; -- called also
<altname>lucifer match</altname>, and <altname>locofoco</altname>, now
most commonly referred to as a <altname>friction match</altname>. See
<er>Locofoco</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of free-swimming macruran
Crustacea, having a slender body and long appendages.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Luciferian</ent>⟦br⟧
